<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-01">
  <title>Module 2: Matrix Addition and Scalar Multiplication</title>

<objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>We will explore the following concepts in this section:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>identity and zero matrices</p></li>
        <li><p>matrix algebra: sums and scalar multiplies</p></li>
      </ul>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply matrix algebra and the zero and identity matrices to solve and analyze matrix equations.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-zero-identity-definitions">
    <title>Definitions: Zero and Identity Matrices</title>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-zero-matrix">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>zero matrix</term> is any matrix whose every entry is zero.
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            0_{2 \times 3} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad 
            0_{2 \times 1} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-identity-and-square">
    <title>Identity Matrices and Square Matrices</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <m>n \times n</m> <term>identity matrix</term> has ones on the main diagonal, otherwise all zeros.
          </p>
          <me>
            I_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}, \quad 
            I_3 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <note>
      <p>
        Any matrix with dimensions <m>n \times n</m> is <term>square</term>. Zero matrices need not be square, but identity matrices must be square.
      </p>
    </note>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-matrix-algebra">
    <title>Matrix Addition and Scalar Multiples</title>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>m \times n</m> matrices. <m>a_{i,j}</m> is the entry of <m>A</m> in row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>, and <m>b_{i,j}</m> is the entry of <m>B</m> in row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>The entries of <m>A + B</m> are <m>a_{i,j} + b_{i,j}</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>If <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, then the entries of <m>cA</m> are <m>ca_{i,j}</m>.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-matrix-algebra-solve">
      <title>Example: Solving for Unknowns</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <me>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \end{pmatrix} + c \begin{pmatrix} 7 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp k \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 15 \amp 10 \amp 17 \\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 16 \end{pmatrix}</me>
          What are the values of <m>c</m> and <m>k</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>c = 2</m> and <m>k = 5</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Looking at the first entry: <m>1 + 7c = 15 \implies 7c = 14 \implies c = 2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Looking at the last entry: <m>6 + ck = 16 \implies 6 + 2k = 16 \implies 2k = 10 \implies k = 5</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-matrix-properties">
    <title>Properties of Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>
    <p>
      Scalar multiples and matrix addition have the expected properties. If <m>r, s \in \mathbb{R}</m> are scalars, and <m>A, B, C</m> are <m>m \times n</m> matrices, then:
    </p>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><p><m>A + 0_{m \times n} = A</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>(A + B) + C = A + (B + C)</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>r(A + B) = rA + rB</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>(r + s)A = rA + sA</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>r(sA) = (rs)A</m></p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <summary>
    <p>We explored the following concepts:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>the identity and zero matrices</p></li>
      <li><p>matrix algebra: sums and scalar multiplies</p></li>
    </ul>
  </summary>

</section>
